specJson.name: brightics.function.clustering$kmeans_silhouette_train_predict
specJson.label: K-Means (Silhouette)
specJson.description:
Kmeans algorithm is an iterative algorithm that tries to partition the dataset into Kpre-defined distinct non-overlapping subgroups (clusters) where each data point belongs to only one group. It tries to make the inter-cluster data points as similar as possible while also keeping the clusters as different (far) as possible. It assigns data points to a cluster such that the sum of the squared distance between the data points and the cluster’s centroid (arithmetic mean of all the data points that belong to that cluster) is at the minimum. The less variation we have within clusters, the more homogeneous (similar) the data points are within the same cluster.

This function using silhouette to find the optimal number of clusters. The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette ranges from −1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate. If many points have a low or negative value, then the clustering configuration may have too many or too few clusters.

Reference: 
+ <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-means_clustering>
+ <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silhouette_(clustering)>
+ <https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.cluster.KMeans.html>
+ <https://towardsdatascience.com/k-means-clustering-algorithm-applications-evaluation-methods-and-drawbacks-aa03e644b48a>

params.label: Input Columns
params.description: Columns to select as input. Only values in numeric type are possible.

params.label: Number of Clusters Set
params.description: The set of the number of clusters to form as well as the number of centroids to generate. The optimal number of clusters is determined by the best silhouette.

params.label: Method for initialization
params.description:
Method for centroids initialization. `k-means++` selects initial cluster centers for k-mean clustering in a smart way to speed up convergence.
    - Available Options : `k-means++`, `random`

params.label: Number of Different Initial Points
params.description: Number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds. The final results will be the best output of `Number of Different Initial Points` consecutive runs in terms of inertia. Inertia means sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center. The larger `Number of Different Initial Points`, the more time it takes to initialize, but the better the initial Centroid values can be.

params.label: Maximum Number of Iterations
params.description: Maximum number of iterations of the k-means algorithm for a single run. The large `Maximum Number of Iterations`, the more time it may take to learn, but the more optimal the results can be.

params.label: Relative Tolerance
params.description: Relative tolerance with regards to inertia to declare convergence. In other words, inertia is calulated for every iteration and if its reduction is less than `Relative Tolerance`, the learning is stopped.

params.label: Precompute Distances
params.description:
Whether precompute distances. If `True`, faster but takes more memory.
    - Available Options : `True`, `False`

params.label: Seed
params.description: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results.

params.label: Number of Jobs
params.description: The number of jobs to use for the computation. This works by computing each of the n_init runs in parallel.

params.label: Kmeans Algorithm
params.description:
K-means algorithm to use. The classical EM-style algorithm is `full'`. The `elkan` variation is more efficient by using the triangle inequality, but currently doesn't support sparse data. `auto` chooses `elkan` for dense data and `full` for sparse data.
    - Available Options : `auto`, `full`, `elkan`

params.label: Number of Samples
params.description: The number of samples data to graph.

md:
# K-Means (Silhouette) This function trains K-Means model(find optimal k using silhouette) and predicts cluster label. ## Description Kmeans algorithm is an iterative algorithm that tries to partition the dataset into Kpre-defined distinct non-overlapping subgroups (clusters) where each data point belongs to only one group. It tries to make the inter-cluster data points as similar as possible while also keeping the clusters as different (far) as possible. It assigns data points to a cluster such that the sum of the squared distance between the data points and the cluster’s centroid (arithmetic mean of all the data points that belong to that cluster) is at the minimum. The less variation we have within clusters, the more homogeneous (similar) the data points are within the same cluster. This function using silhouette to find the optimal number of clusters. The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette ranges from −1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate. If many points have a low or negative value, then the clustering configuration may have too many or too few clusters. Reference: + + + + ## Properties ### VA #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one numeric column for training. #### OUTPUT 1. **table**: (Table) A result Table that contains input Table's columns and prediction column as `Prediction Column Name`. 2. **model**: (Model) K-Means model. #### PARAMETER 1. **Input Columns***: Columns to select as input. Only values in numeric type are possible. 2. **Number of Clusters Set**: The set of the number of clusters to form as well as the number of centroids to generate. The optimal number of clusters is determined by the best silhouette. 3. **Prediction Column Name**: A name of prediction column. 4. **Method for initialization**: Method for centroids initialization. `k-means++` selects initial cluster centers for k-mean clustering in a smart way to speed up convergence. * Available Options: `k-means++`, `random` 5. **Number of Different Initial Points**: Number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds. The final results will be the best output of `Number of Different Initial Points` consecutive runs in terms of inertia. Inertia means sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center. The larger `Number of Different Initial Points`, the more time it takes to initialize, but the better the initial Centroid values can be. 6. **Maximum Number of Iterations**: Maximum number of iterations of the k-means algorithm for a single run. The large `Maximum Number of Iterations`, the more time it may take to learn, but the more optimal the results can be. 7. **Relative Tolerance**: Relative tolerance with regards to inertia to declare convergence. In other words, inertia is calulated for every iteration and if its reduction is less than `Relative Tolerance`, the learning is stopped. 8. **Precompute Distances**: Whether precompute distances. If `True`, faster but takes more memory. * Available Options: `True`, `False` * 9. **Seed**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. 10. **Number of Jobs**: The number of jobs to use for the computation. This works by computing each of the n_init runs in parallel. 11. **Kmeans Algorithm**: K-means algorithm to use. The classical EM-style algorithm is `full'`. The `elkan` variation is more efficient by using the triangle inequality, but currently doesn't support sparse data. `auto` chooses `elkan` for dense data and `full` for sparse data. * Available Options: `auto`, `full`, `elkan` 12. **Number of Samples**: The number of samples data to graph. 13. **Group By**: Columns to group by. ### Python #### USAGE ``` kmeans_silhouette_train_predict(table, input_cols, n_clusters_list=range(2, 10), prediction_col='prediction', init='k-means++', n_init=10, max_iter=300, tol=1e-4, precompute_distances='auto', seed=None, n_jobs=1, algorithm='auto', n_samples=None) ``` #### INPUT 1. **table***: (Table) Training data in a Table. It must contain at least one numeric column for training. #### OUTPUT 1. **table**: (Table) A result Table that contains input Table's columns and prediction column as `prediction_col`. 2. **model**: (Model) K-Means model. #### PARAMETER 1. **input_cols***: Columns to select as input. Only values in numeric type are possible. * Type: *list[str]* 2. **n_clusters_list**: The set of the number of clusters to form as well as the number of centroids to generate. The optimal number of clusters is determined by the best silhouette. * Type: *list[int]* * Default value: range(2,10) 3. **prediction_col**: A name of prediction column. * Type: *str* * Default value: 'prediction' 4. **init**: Method for centroids initialization. `k-means++` selects initial cluster centers for k-mean clustering in a smart way to speed up convergence. * Type: *str* * Default / Range: k-means++ ( k-means++ | random ) 5. **n_init**: Number of time the k-means algorithm will be run with different centroid seeds. The final results will be the best output of `Number of Different Initial Points` consecutive runs in terms of inertia. Inertia means sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center. The larger `Number of Different Initial Points`, the more time it takes to initialize, but the better the initial Centroid values can be. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 3 (value >= 1) 6. **max_iter**: Maximum number of iterations of the k-means algorithm for a single run. The large `Maximum Number of Iterations`, the more time it may take to learn, but the more optimal the results can be. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 300 (value >= 1) 7. **tol**: Relative tolerance with regards to inertia to declare convergence. In other words, inertia is calulated for every iteration and if its reduction is less than `Relative Tolerance`, the learning is stopped. * Type: *float* * Default value: 0.0001 8. **precompute_distances**: Whether precompute distances. If `True`, faster but takes more memory. * Type: *bool* * Default value: True 9. **seed**: Random seed. Use the same seed in order to reproduce the same results. * Type: *int* * Default value: None 10. **n_jobs**: The number of jobs to use for the computation. This works by computing each of the n_init runs in parallel. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: 1 (value >= 1) 11. **algorithm**: K-means algorithm to use. The classical EM-style algorithm is `full'`. The `elkan` variation is more efficient by using the triangle inequality, but currently doesn't support sparse data. `auto` chooses `elkan` for dense data and `full` for sparse data. * Type: *str* * Default / Range: auto ( auto | full | elkan ) 12. **n_samples**: The number of samples data to graph. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: None (value >= 0) 13. **group_by**: Columns to group by. * Type: *list[str]* ## Example ### VA **[Related Tutorial]** **[Sample Model]**
In this tutorial workflow, sample_iris data is used to train and predict a k-means model. The generated model is afterward applied to a test data set to predict cluster label, by using K-Means Predict function. The parameter settings used in the function are shown below. ##### ++Parameters++ 1. **Input Columns*** : sepal_length, sepal_width 2. **Number of Clusters set** : 3, 4, 5, 6 3. **Prediction Column Name:** : prediction 4. **Method for initialization** : k-means++ 5. **Number of Different Initial Points** : 10 6. **Maximum Number of Iterations** : 300 7. **Relative Tolerance** : 0.0001 8. **Precompute Distances** : True 9. **Seed** : None 10. **Number of Jobs** : 1 11. **Kmeans Algorithm** : auto 12. **Number of Samples** : None 13. **Group By** : None ### Python ``` from brightics.function.clustering import kmeans_silhouette_train_predict input_table = inputs[0] result = kmeans_silhouette_train_predict(table=input_table, input_cols=['sepal_length', 'sepal_width'], n_clusters_list=[3, 4, 5, 6], prediction_col='prediction', init='k-means++', n_init=10, max_iter=300, tol=0.0001, precompute_distances='auto', seed=None, n_jobs=1, algorithm='auto', n_samples=None) output_table = result['out_table'] output_model = result['model'] ```
In this python script, sample_iris data is used to train and predict a k-means model. The generated model is afterward applied to a test data set to predict cluster label, by using kmeans_predict function.
